FY 2025 Plans:
This project will fund civilian salaries and operating costs for OPTEVFOR.

- Continue efforts to enhance and improve test processes and products in support of increasing the value
of OT&E; tailoring of processes and methods to ensure relevance for capability development and fielding
approaches spanning the adaptive acquisition framework (AAF), and maturing OT&E concepts and methods for
Agile software-based systems.

- Continue to support OPNAV N9 Naval Capabilities Integration Process (NCIP) effort. Participate in Navy
Concepts of Employment (CONEMPS) working groups. Coordinate with Warfighting Development Centers
(WDCs) to share data/knowledge. Contribute to U.S. Fleet Forces/Commander, Pacific Fleet Warfare
Capabilities Baseline (USFF/CPF WCB). In these ways, support the Navy's examination of capability across
all platforms, networks, weapons, or sensors. - Analyze performance across warfare domains; continue to
collaborate across warfare domains to maximize lessons learned, share resources, gain efficiencies in testing,
and provide value to the Fleet, WDCs, and acquisition decision makers.

- Bridge Fleet-to-acquisition communication seams through greater external engagement with WDCs;
implementation of Capabilities Based Test and Evaluation (CBTE) across the Enterprise, including Cyber OT&E;
and continuously improving our operations, training, and T&E data management.

- OPTEVFOR uses a strategic framework to align command initiatives with Navy leadership and the National
strategic environment. The framework establishes a Problem-Solving Canvas (PSC) for each command
initiative to ensure appropriate contribution to the Navy-wide "Get Real Get Better" (GRGB) call to action.
The framework may be binned in four focus areas: Fleet Engagement, Acquisition Engagement, Command
Operations, and Military Programs and Infrastructure. The focus areas support the NAVPLAN Implementation
Framework (NIF) pillars and are enabled by the use of the Cross Service Operation Test Agency (OTA) Core
Test Principles and a command-wide metrics program. Fleet Engagement initiatives include Naval Aviation End-
to-End Optimization, use and improvement of OT results to inform Carrier Strike Group (CSG) readiness for the
high-end-fight, and potential application of OT&E concepts in Fleet experimentation. Acquisition Engagement
initiatives include analyzing and improving approaches to T&E data management to increase the efficiency

