A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
Mission: The Fleet Experimentation (FLEX) program seeks out and examines potential materiel and non-materiel solutions (initiatives) to the Fleet's highest priority
warfighting gaps and generates data-driven findings and actionable recommendations to resolve or mitigate those gaps. As part of a multi-year campaign, 10 to 15 major
analytic experimentation activities take place annually that include workshops, war-games, and with a focus on live force, operationally oriented at-sea events.

The FLEX Program is owned by Commander U.S. Fleet Forces Command (CUSFFC), Commander U.S. Pacific Fleet (CPF), and Commander U.S. Naval Forces
Europe - Africa (CNE-AF). The three four-star Fleet Commanders identify the Fleet priorities and warfighting gaps for FLEX to address, and Navy Warfare Development
Center (NWDC), as the Executive Agent (EA), designs, plans, executes, analyzes, and reports on the FLEX initiatives.

Commanders' FLEX guidance is linked to the January 2024 Chief of Naval Operations (CNO) Navigation Plan (NAVPLAN) direction to continue refinement of concepts
and capabilities through experimentation. FLEX priorities are also aligned to the Warfighting Integration NAVPLAN Implementation Framework (WIN NIF) Operating
Review for the CNO that identifies the North Star, supporting pillars, and approach. FLEX initiatives are tied to CNO-approved Distributed Maritime Operations (DMO)
and Joint Warfighting Concept (JWC) concept capability requirements, Fleet warfighting gaps, and Key Operational Problems (KOP). FLEX aligns with National Defense
Strategy priorities, lines of effort 1 (lethality) and 3 (reform), and numerous other strategic guidance documents highlighting the need to increase organizational learning
and capability development in experimentation, wargames, and exercises.

USFFC N8/N9-manages the FLEX investment -- $12.585M (FY26) to support planning, execution, analysis, and reporting for analytically rigorous experiments
leveraging Limited Objective Experiments (LOE) and scheduled fleet exercises.

